s, oral interviews, fact sheets, blogs, films, and television shows. Together, they explore the stories we tell about depression: its contested causes; its gendering; the transformations in identity that it entails; and the problems it presents for communication, associated as it is with stigma and shame.Unlike certain physical illnesses, such as cancer, depression is stigmatized—sometimes as a nonproblem (the sufferer should "snap out of it") and sometimes as the slippery slope to madness. Thus, depression narratives have their work cut out for them. This book highlights the work these stories do, including bringing meaning to sufferers, explaining depression, justifying therapies and treatments, and reducing the burden of shame—accounting for a suffering that is, in the end, unaccountable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aHealth and Medicine : Health and Society. 4aPsychology : Mental Health. 4aPsychology : Psychological Approaches to Literature. 4aPsychology : Psychotherapy. 4aPsychology : Social Psychology. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBeilke, Debra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenzon, Kiki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanch, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Hilary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Mark A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyer, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmons, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngland, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanzer, Carol, econtri